<DESCRIPT>  BOOK; HISTORY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  PLANNING to read Alexandra Ripley's sequel to "Gone With the Wind"?;   Bear in
mind that the story line for "Scarlett" will be faithful to Margaret
Mitchell's original novel rather than to the movie, which took some liberties
with Mitchell's plot.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHEN WE LAST LEFT SCARLETT . . .  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related story page 5D of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Here's a quick review of how things stood at the conclusion of the book:;  
(check) Scarlett has been deserted by Rhett, leaving her to scheme about some
way to get him back. She is living with her two children, Wade Hampton (from
her marriage to Charles Hamilton) and Ella Lorena (from her marriage to Frank
Kennedy). Bonnie Butler, Scarlett and Rhett's daughter from their marriage,
died of a broken neck sustained in a fall from her pony.;   (check) Rhett
leaves Atlanta and heads for his native Charleston.;   (check) Ashley Wilkes'
beloved wife, Melanie, has just died, leaving him alone with their young son,
Beauregard. Melanie made Scarlett promise to take care of Ashley.;   (check)
Mammy is living at Tara with Scarlett's sister, Suellen, and Suellen's
husband, Will Benteen.;   (check) India Wilkes, Ashley's sister, is living in
Aunt Pittypat's Atlanta home and remains alienated from Scarlett, whom she
caught in Ashley's arms. Both India and Pittypat remain unmarried, Atlanta's
"old maids.";   (check) Careen, Scarlett's youngest sister, is in a Charleston
convent, still mourning her beau's death in the war.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  -- Dennis Love  </BYLINE>
